I haven't figured out how to use read-write lock in our condition yet. I'll think about it. Thanks.

Back to `readBufferLock`, considring timer thread only, I think we can use only one lock, which is more effective. As follows:

```java
public void write(List<T> data) {
    writeBufferLock.lock();
    try {
        data.forEach(writeBufferPointer::accept);
    } finally {
        writeBufferLock.unlock();
    }
}

public List<T> read() {
    writeBufferLock.lock();
    try {
        BufferedData<T> tempPointer = writeBufferPointer;
        writeBufferPointer = readBufferPointer;
        readBufferPointer = tempPointer;
    } finally {
        writeBufferLock.unlock();
    }
    readBufferPointer.read();
}
```

Considering annother situation with multiple reader thread, read-buffer lock is necessary. As follows.

```java
public void write(List<T> data) {
    writeBufferLock.lock();
    try {
        data.forEach(writeBufferPointer::accept);
    } finally {
        writeBufferLock.unlock();
    }
}

public List<T> read() {
    readBufferLock.lock();
    try {
        writeBufferLock.lock();
        try {
            BufferedData<T> tempPointer = writeBufferPointer;
            writeBufferPointer = readBufferPointer;
            readBufferPointer = tempPointer;
        } finally {
            writeBufferLock.unlock();
        }

        readBufferPointer.read();
    } finally {
        readBufferLock.unlock();
    }
}
```

Maybe the second way is better? Maybe there are some features need to use `ReadWriteSafeCache` in multiple reader way in the future.

